| Topic Focus – Bridging Local and Remote Port Forwarding  
          |  
          | Purpose:  
          |     - Chain multiple SSH tunnels to access internal services securely  
          |     - Combines `-L` (Local Forwarding) and `-D` (Dynamic Forwarding) across hosts  

          | Step 1 – Local Port Forwarding to Internal Host:  
          |     Internet_Host → Internal SSH Gateway  
          |     - Command:  
          |         → `ssh student@172.16.1.15 -L 2222:localhost:1122`  
          |         → or  
          |         → `ssh -L 2222:localhost:1122 student@172.16.1.15`  
          |     - Effect:  
          |         → Binds port 2222 on Internet_Host to port 1122 on Internal_Host  

          | Step 2 – Dynamic Port Forwarding over Local Tunnel:  
          |     Internet_Host → SOCKS Proxy via Local Port  
          |     - Command:  
          |         → `ssh student@localhost -p 2222 -D 9050 2>/dev/null`  
          |         → or  
          |         → `ssh -D 9050 student@localhost -p 2222 2>/dev/null`  
          |     - Effect:  
          |         → Creates SOCKS proxy on port 9050 through the chained tunnel  
          |         → Enables dynamic routing of traffic through internal network  

